<title>Microrobots</title>
<center><h1>Microrobots</h1></center>

One of the goals of the Microrobotics group of the <!WA0><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/microrobots//">MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory</a> is to develop new techniques for the construction of miniature <!WA1><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/mobile-robots">mobile robots</a>.  In addition to building cool little robots, we also are exploring different ways to take advantage of their size for useful and interesting applications.<p>

<h2>Current Projects</h2>

<strong><!WA2><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/ants">
<!WA3><IMG align=left SRC="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/ants/fingrant-25.jpg"> The Ants</a>
</strong><br>
<!WA4><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/microrobots/">Microrobots</a> designed to explore ideas
about robotic communities.  One of the potential applications for this
research is <!WA5><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/eod-robots/"> explosive ordnance
disposal</a>.<br clear=all><p>

BF Skinny<br>
A cubic-inch robot designed to compete in the 1995 International Microrobot Maze Competition.<p>

<!WA6><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/mars-rovers/rockettes.html"><!WA7><IMG align=left SRC="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/mars-rovers/rockettes-on-mars-small">
<strong>The Rockettes</strong><br>
</a>The goal of the <!WA8><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/mars-rovers/rockettes.html">Rockettes</a> project is to build
 small, 10 gram <!WA9><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/mobile-robots">mobile robots</a> for
planetary exploration. That way, we can send many
<!WA10><a href="http://www.ai.mit.edu/projects/microrobots">microrobots</a> instead of a single larger one.
<br clear=all><p>

